Journal = {{ROCK MECHANICS AND ROCK ENGINEERING}},
Year = {{2015}},
Volume = {{48}},
Number = {{1}},
Pages = {{289-303}},
Month = {{JAN}},
Abstract = {{Based on the radiated energy of 133 rock bursts monitored by a
   microseismic technique at the Jinping II hydropower station, in Sichuan
   province, China, we analyzed the advantages and disadvantages of
   qualitative classification methods for the rock burst intensity. Then,
   we investigated the characteristics, magnitude, and laws of the radiated
   energy, as well as the relationship between the rock burst radiated
   energy and intensity. Then, we selected the energy as an evaluation
   index for the rock burst intensity classification, and proposed a new
   rock burst intensity quantitative classification method, which utilized
   the hierarchical clustering analysis technique with the complete-linkage
   method. Next, we created a new set of criteria for the quantitative
   classification of the rock burst intensity based on radiated energy and
   surrounding rock damage severity. The new criteria classified the rock
   burst intensity into five levels: extremely intense, intense, moderate,
   weak, and none, and the common logarithms of the radiated energy of each
   level were > 7 lg(E/J), > 4 lg(E/J) and < 7 lg(E/J), > 2 lg(E/J) and < 4
   lg(E/J), > 1 lg(E/J) and < 2 lg(E/J), and < 1 lg(E/J), respectively.
   Finally, we investigated the factors influencing the classification, and
   verified its feasibility and applicability via several practical rock
   burst examples.}},
