   seasonality, and fish growth phase. From March 2010 to March 2011,
   sixty-three specimens of O. niloticus in three growth phases (i.e.,
   initial, intermediate, and final) were collected. All fish specimens
   were infested with at least one ectoparasite species (prevalence =
   100\%). Five species of protozoans (Trichodina compacta, Trichodina
   magna, Ichthyophthirius multifiliis, Piscinoodinium pillulare, and
   Epistylis sp.) and five species of monogenoids (Cichlidogyrus halli,
   Cichlidogyrus thurstonae, Cichlidogyrus sp. 1, Scutogyrus longicornis,
   and Gyrodactylus sp.) were observed. The abundance of Trichodina spp.
   and the prevalence of Epistylis sp. were higher in the dry season, and
   the prevalence of C. halli was higher in the rainy season. For the
   majority of ectoparasites found in this study, fish in the intermediate
   and final phases had higher parasitism rates than those in the initial
   phase. The data presented may help fish farmers to understand the
   parasite dynamics of the fish species studied in cage-farming systems.}},
