Abstract = {{We compared two types of light traps used for monitoring mosquito
   abundance in the hydroelectric reservoir of Simplicio, Alem Paraiba -
   Minas Gerais. Mosquitoes were captured bimonthly using automatic CDC and
   Shannon traps before the filling of the hydroelectric plant reservoir
   from December 2008 to December 2009. In total, 1474 specimens from 13
   genera were captured. Among the captured specimens, several species
   known to be vectors of disease-causing agents for humans and/or animals
   were identified, including Anopheles aquasalis, Aedes albopictus,
   Coquillettidia venezuelensis, Haemagogus leucocelaenus, and Aedes
   scapularis. Sampling efficacybetween the four capture sites was not
   found to be significantly different, irrespective of species captured or
   type of trap used. Poor correlation (r(x, y) = -0.0444) between the
   number of mosquito species and capture site was observed when not
   influenced by the type of trap used. Among the installation sites of the
   CDC and Shannon traps in the areas investigated, CDC traps fixed in
   livestock shelters obtained an overall higher abundance of species
   captured.}},
