Title = {{Dietary energy requirements of young adult women in China by the doubly
   labeled water method}},
Journal = {{ASIA PACIFIC JOURNAL OF CLINICAL NUTRITION}},
Year = {{2010}},
Volume = {{19}},
Number = {{4}},
Pages = {{520-525}},
Abstract = {{Objective: The current recommendations on dietary energy requirements in
   China have been based on total energy expenditure (TEE) derived from
   theoretical factorial calculations expressed as multiples of basal
   energy expenditure (BEE). Few direct measurements of TEE and BEE have
   been conducted in Chinese people. This study was designed to measure the
   TEE and BEE of healthy, light active women of normal body weight living
   in China, and to evaluate the recommendations on dietary energy
   requirements by comparing the data correspondingly. Design: 16 healthy
   female adults aged 22.1 +/- 1.2 y with a body mass index (in kg/m(2)) of
   20.4 +/- 1.7 were selected. Under well-controlled conditions, TEEs were
   determined by using the doubly labeled water method. At the same time,
   BEEs were measured by using indirect calorimetry. Results: Measured TEE
   was 1380 +/- 118 kcal/d, which was close to the value of energy intake
   (1381 +/- 96 kcal/d). Comparing the measured TEE with the recommended
   (Chinese recommended value for this group is 2100 kcal/d), the
   recommended was substantially higher than the measured by 15\% or so.
   Meanwhile, the calculated BEE (1230 +/- 65 kcal/d) by using the adjusted
   Schofield equation proposed by the Chinese Nutrition Society was
   significantly higher (p <0.001) than the measured BEE (1130 +/- 110
   kcal/d), by 9\% or so. Conclusion: Current recommended energy intake for
   young adult women may need to be revised on the basis of measured TEE
   and BEE.}},
