   dam flooding in southern Brazil}},
Journal = {{NORTH-WESTERN JOURNAL OF ZOOLOGY}},
Year = {{2009}},
Volume = {{5}},
Number = {{1}},
Pages = {{53-60}},
Month = {{JUN}},
Abstract = {{We describe aspects of the feeding ecology of a population of the
   colubrid snake Philodryas olfersii in central Rio Grande do Sul State,
   Brazil. Based on specimens obtained during the fauna rescue operation of
   Dona Francisca hydroelectric powerplant, we conducted the first analysis
   of the diet of a snake during artificial flooding of an area in Brazil.
   Females attained larger body sizes than males, and ingested heavier
   prey. We observed a high proportion of recently-fed individuals; mammals
   were the most frequent prey, followed by birds and frogs. Our results
   differ drastically from those obtained for P. olfersii in adjacent
   areas. The frequency of items and dominance of major prey categories in
   the diet of this snake seem to have been influenced by an unusual
   exposure of rodents and, consequently, changes in prey delectability
   resulting from the dam flooding.}},
